Inflation slides in food
The accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the vertiginous growth of food prices.
The price rise in November has been higher than expected in the 13 Eurozone countries, recording - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent, the EU Statistics Office based in Luxembourg announced.
Official forecasts gave as likely only 3 percent, Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian emitter banks, did not cut the basic interest, with the pretext that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the trap 22: “there is to negotiate” on inflation so that subsequently it does not have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the record of twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the Eurozone has led to food and energy prices.
The quotations at the end of the wheat increased by 88 percent and the soya quotations reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, it had to pay a lot more in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold almost $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1% to 2.5%, while in 2009 it will decline to 1.9.
According to analysts, the annual inflation will remain around 3 percent over the next 3 or 4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double the interest rates during the year 2008.
