In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants.
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals produced first by the misuse of antibiotics.
The reigning hygiene circumstances in hospitals, the climbing of beds and the overload of staff do not favour the control of infections - says the doctor-head department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago a MRSA infection has been diagnosed at the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the antibiotic resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A wound from a serious car accident was given high from the hospital and the same patient shortly after it had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then it has not been able to perform an important surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10, this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multiresistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, the head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely, the rest has no information.
Nearly two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of humans carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once antibiotics are applied excessively or unduely, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics are transformed into very antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly contain in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause severe hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia first in patients with transitory or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened body, elderly or low-weight people.
According to the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special in MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nursing staff care them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are examined in advance to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but not even thus infection can be avoided in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples.
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, however current national hospital circumstances do not favour for the prevention of formation and contagion with multiresistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly households, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the sick who carry the MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come out to public light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the doctor-chef of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous commands for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for the treatment of infections and pathological images.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Saving with Desinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases the MRSA is infected from one patient to another through the health staff.
Therefore, the washing of the hands, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is contagious through drops transmission and direct contact between people, but in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, the hospitals rooms are often overwhelmed, the beds are often very together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation it is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater likelihood of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are met, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the pathogen infection can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treatment of infection with MRSA is a huge expenditure for the National Disease Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against it.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
Apparently the program has success, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show tendance to decrease in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multiresistant agents (including MRSA) and the hospital infections that are due to these pathogens.
