More €400 million for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed on Friday in Budapest three credit limit agreements for a total value of 400 million euros to finance infrastructures for education, transport and the environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of 300 million euros to finance in the Hungarian budget the transport and environment protection projects, which will be carried out from the cohesion funds, of which the parties had already previously signed a credit contract for a value of 100 million euros, the contract they just signed refers to the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The credit contract of €150 million is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of 300 million euros for this goal of Hungary, on the use of the remaining 150 million euros the decision will be made later, by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will use primarily for the University of Debrecen’s innovation and research project.
During the conversations they also covered the topic of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
The agreement was reached that when Hungary ultimates with the EU the details of the Metro financing, they will again deal with the issue whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has funded a total of 113 projects in Hungary for a value of €8.4 billion.
The interest rate of the credits is adjusted to EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grant period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
