Fodor and the six per hundred Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor the meetings at the level of experts will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue the negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries in the world deliberate on the Balí Road Sheet which provides on the efforts after the emission reduction period, established in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Currently there are animated discussions on the particular between developing countries and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on accurate figures, although it tends to reach an agreement that compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020 the emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major topic of the conference is whether the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are or not willing to offer material and technological assistance to the countries in need of it.
It has also reached an agreement on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac es Profit".
The six per hundred of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Hydrology Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signature of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister said the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 level, regardless of whether the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed or not, and is willing to commit to decrease by even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to undertake commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signing the 1997 Kyoto Protocol undertaken to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states undertaken to meet a 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet, the Ministry of Environment’s press release said.
It’s a lot what’s on the game in Bali, since within two years it will have to sign the international climate policy agreement in the long-term, because if not, it’s sure that its entry into force would be delayed for after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, whose need was warned in its latest report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN that deals with climate change, which obtained the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would suffer a delay and could not be prevented by a rise of more than 2°C of the average Earth temperature, which, according to scientists, would have unmeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
The British army units on a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularise themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of the YouTube services: the special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helm are controlled in the general body of operations of Kandahar, then they are sent to London to be charged to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers that have been charged in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Defence Ministry registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and published videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the British Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operations in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present to the public the true goal of the presence of the British army abroad.
This type of propaganda practically doesn’t cost anything compared to conventional recruitment television spots – Defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told BBC – instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason of being of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans Played a Video Game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the recelosely edited and censored recordings, on the distributor appear also amateur videos, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the “official” propaganda films, slightly hypocritic, officials talk as a maximum of losses, without presenting however the bloody part of the battles.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way for recruitment with the free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
