In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers in the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays – that the coming year will be less – the working days are reorganized.
Not even in the EU or in North America the holidays are unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national feast, state feast and holidays.
The holidays are mainly related to religious holidays and historical feasts.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is holidays – this last above all so that those who passed celebrating the old year can rest.
Over the course of the year we have eleven holidays written with red numbers in the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and October 23 in memory of the revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the Foundation of the State, on the 1st of May the Day of Work, on the 1st and 2nd of November we remind our families and friends of the dead.
Moreover, in our country are two-day holidays the Easter of Resurrection, the Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it is often bridge when before or after the party there is a single working day.
In exchange for the weekends so extended, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of work that regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or after the party.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory in return for companies and services institutions that, due to their function, work uninterrupted even during the holidays.
