A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the destinations of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archive documents, stored over 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not until here consultable only for a “humanitarian” purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or its right-wing members.
The eleven states responsible for their management – such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to search engines and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has ended, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to do searches “particularly on the displacements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these files administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, such as Germany, opposed the public opening of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or the mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or of the detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: to find the landlords deported or subjected to mandatory work and eventually to provide them a proof of their internation, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with dozens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen looks at a limited interest.
"There's nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Search for Antisemitism at the Technische Universität of Berlin, said in 2006.
