Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force on 1 November
Parallel to its parliamentary trial, which ended today with the vote by the Congress of the amendments incorporated to the project in the Senate, the Government has submitted to public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim that both enter into force before the year ends.
Representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the effort made by Deputies and Senators to negotiate and consensate the best regulations in order to ensure the protection of investors and to detailly regulate the activity of the entities so that the markets work efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, implies the modernization of the financial markets, while strengthening the investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and fostering cooperation between the different supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulations will allow financial advisory services to both specialized firms and physical or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory societies (AFI), which join securities, securities agencies and portfolio-managing societies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The law also obliges investment services companies to disclose on the market information about the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management forms and requires them to carry a record of all the transactions they carry out, to facilitate the supervision by the CNMV.
