Venus is the Earth’s Twin Brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to the Earth, something that has not yet been proposed.The European "Venus Express" probe discovered rays in the atmosphere and remolins in the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had the suspicion that there could be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays walk at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller life, the rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, on their part, would have given origin to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if there was life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there cannot be life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface reigns temperatures of 500°C, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
“Probably, Venus is a ‘diabolic’ twin of the Earth, but it’s still a twin,” Russell said.
The main goal of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many “Nature” articles, according to the researchers’ opinion, emphasize not only the unity of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had supposed,” the ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vórtice formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds of wind flows in the high Earth atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has a mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost so large.
This planet is also called a star of alba or a star of evening orbiting around the Sun for 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day on Venus is equal to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much similar to Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
In the two planets water had been aggregated that in the Earth was left in the oceans, but in Venus was dissolved in the universe.
While carbon dioxide on Earth had become carbon stones, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
